==形態描述==
[[File:Haeckel_Ciliata.jpg|thumb]]
不同种的砂壳纤毛虫的壳或胴甲的长度和口径变化很大。壳长最大的记录是[[巨拟网纹虫|巨拟网纹虫]]（''Parafavella gigantea''）壳为750 μm(Marshall, 1969)，最小的壳为[[极小领细壳虫|极小领细壳虫]]（''Stenosemella perpusilla''），壳长13 μm(Hada, 1970)。同一个种中，不同海域不同个体间的长度差可达300 μm。例如，巨拟网纹虫的最大记录750 μm (Marshall, 1969)，但是大多为337-576 μm(Campbell, 1942)。同一种中不同个体壳的大小可能是年龄的标志，小壳是幼体，大壳则是成熟的个体(Gold and Morales, 1976b)。

They were among the many planktonic microorganisms featured in Ernst's <!-- [[Haeckel|Haeckel]] -->[[恩斯特·海克尔|恩斯特·海克尔]]'s classic work popularizing the beauty of the natural world "Art forms in Nature" (<!-- [[Kunstformen_der_Natur|Kunstformen der Natur]] -->[[自然界的藝術形態|自然界的藝術形態]]).

如同其他[[原生生物|原生生物]]，砂壳纤毛虫屬於一種複雜的單細胞[[真核生物|真核生物]]。牠們是丁丁是[[異養水生生物|異養水生生物]]（heterotrophic aquatic organisms）， 以能進行[[光合作用|光合作用]]的[[藻類|藻類]]和[[细菌|细菌]]為食<ref name=":0">{{Cite book |url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/793006266 |title=The biology and ecology of tintinnid ciliates : models for marine plankton|last=Montagnes|first=D. J. S.|date=2012|publisher=Wiley|others=Dolan, John R. (John Richard), 1955-|year=|isbn=9780470671511|location=Hoboken, NJ|pages=85–121|chapter=Ecophysiology and behavior of tintinnids|oclc=793006266}}</ref>，均為 體長介乎20到200[[微米|微米]]的[[浮游生物|微型浮游生物]]。Tintinnids are found in marine and freshwaters. However, they are most common in salt water and are usually present in concentrations of about 100 a liter but can reach abundances of several thousand per <!-- [[litre|litre]] -->[[公升|公升]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/793006266|title=The biology and ecology of tintinnid ciliates : models for marine plankton|last=McManus|first=G. B.|last2=Santoferrara|first2=L. F.|date=2012|publisher=Wiley|others=Dolan, John R. (John Richard), 1955-|year=|isbn=9780470671511|location=Hoboken, NJ|pages=198–213|chapter=Tintinnids in microzooplankton communities|oclc=793006266}}</ref> Characteristics of their lorica, or shells, are classically used to distinguish the roughly 1000 species described. However, in recent years application of histological and molecular techniques have led to many taxonomic revisions.<ref>{{Cite book |url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/793006266 |title=The biology and ecology of tintinnid ciliates : models for marine plankton |last=Agatha |first=Sabine |last2=Strûder-Kypke |first2=M. C. |date=2012 |publisher=Wiley |others=Dolan, John R. (John Richard), 1955-|year=|isbn=9780470671511|location=Hoboken, NJ|pages=42–84|chapter=Systematics and Evolution of tintinnid ciliates|oclc=793006266}}</ref>

Many species appear to have wide distributions (for example from the <!-- [[Chesapeake_Bay|Chesapeake Bay]] -->[[切萨皮克湾|切萨皮克湾]] to <!-- [[New_Caledonia|New Caledonia]] -->[[新喀里多尼亞|新喀里多尼亞]]) while others are restricted to certain areas, such as arctic waters or coastal seas.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/793006266|title=The biology and ecology of tintinnid ciliates : models for marine plankton|last=Dolan|first=J. R.|last2=Pierce|first2=R. W.|date=2012|publisher=Wiley|others=Dolan, John R. (John Richard), 1955-|year=|isbn=9780470671511|location=Hoboken, NJ|pages=214–243|chapter=Diversity and distributions of tintinnds|oclc=793006266}}</ref> Nonetheless, in any given locale dozens of species can be found. Like other members of the microzooplankton (such as {{tsl|en|oligotrich||oligotrich}} ciliates, heterotrophic <!-- [[dinoflagellate|dinoflagellate]] -->[[双鞭毛虫门|双鞭毛虫门]]s, {{tsl|en|radiolarian||radiolarian}}s, etc.), tintinnids are a vital link in aquatic food chains as they are the '<!-- [[herbivore|herbivore]] -->[[食草动物|食草动物]]s' of the plankton. They feed on <!-- [[phytoplankton|phytoplankton]] -->[[浮游植物|浮游植物]] (algae and cyanobacteria) and in turn act as food for larger organisms such as <!-- [[copepod|copepod]] -->[[橈腳類|橈腳類]]s (small <!-- [[crustacean|crustacean]] -->[[甲殼亞門|甲殼亞門]]s) and larval fish.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/793006266|title=The biology and ecology of tintinnid ciliates : models for marine plankton|last=Stoecker|first=D. K.|date=2012|publisher=Wiley|others=Dolan, John R. (John Richard), 1955-|year=|isbn=9780470671511|location=Hoboken, NJ|pages=122–144|chapter=Predators of tintinnids|oclc=793006266|chapter-format=}}</ref>

The color image on the right is a specimen of ''Dictyocysta mitra'' from the Bay of <!-- [[Villefranche-sur-Mer|Villefranche]] -->[[滨海自由城|滨海自由城]] in the Mediterranean Sea. The hair-like projections pointing out of the top of the shell are the cilia of the cell. The cilia generate a water flow across the mouth of the cell, bringing food into contact and move the tintinnid. Their swimming pattern is rather 'jumpy'- or dancing- they are part of the 'choreotrichs' which means dancing hairs from their swimming behaviour and cilia.<ref name=":0" />

